text: <@U05AFDRH8AJ> has joined the channel

The application for the MBA Latin America study abroad is open.  Students can access the applications by going to Home - ISP (<http://byu.edu|byu.edu>) (<https://isp.byu.edu/>) or through the Kennedy Center website at Apply Now (<http://byu.edu|byu.edu>) (<https://kennedy.byu.edu/isp-apply>).

The application deadline is 10 November.
.
*There is a $35 application fee. Students do not require an essay or references but will need to write N/A in those areas or the application will show as incomplete.*

The cost of the 14 day program will be approximately $4000-$4200. The Kennedy Center will charge $3000 and we will pay for the international flight tickets (to and from SLC) individually since there are some flights with longer layovers that save a few hundred dollars that some students may prefer.

We plan to have another meeting next week for all of the registered students to finalize the itinerary ( Easter Island, Patagonia or the Galapagos).

Although this trip is normally reserved for the second year students, since we are all traveling on our personal time off from school, 1st year students can also participate.

text:
Some more details on your options...
• Easter Island: a few large, inanimate, frowning faces made of stone on a single, mostly treeless, very remote, patch of ground.
• Galapagos Islands: multiple beautiful islands filled with hundreds of endemic species that don't exist anywhere else in the world, including giant tortoises (up to 900 lbs, 4'3'' long) :turtle:, marine iguanas (basically just small godzillas) :lizard:, lava lizards :volcano:, flightless cormorants :eagle:, blue-footed boobys :bird:, and tropical penguins:penguin:(the only penguins in the northern hemisphere :dancing-penguin:). Also dolphins :dolphin:, sharks :shark:, coral :coral:, and snorkeling :diving_mask:. And it's the #3 destination in Central/South America (<https://travel.usnews.com/rankings/best-central-and-south-american-vacations/>)!!!

<!channel> I put you in here if you had reacted to any of the other posts about the info session/competition. 

The info session will be on Tuesday 10/17, 5p - 6/630p in 484, the other side of the tanner building. 

• We’ll do an overview of how acquisitions work and why it’s a great path to go down
• We’ll have Ryan Salmon (class of 2019) talk about his experience acquiring companies during/after the MBA program
• We’ll add lots of context and answer questions about the Acquisition Competition 
Some brief details on the competition: 
• It will be held at Kiln in Provo on Saturday, November 18th, in the morning. Likely 9:30am but it may move earlier depending on when the BYU Oklahoma game kicks off. 
• It will not conflict with the VCIC competition, you can do both. All proposals for the acquisition competition will be due November 3rd. 
• I’m attaching the prompt for the competition here, take a look at it and y’all can get started this weekend if you’d like — or wait until Tuesday for more context, but the prompt will remain the same. 
It’s worth pointing out that we’ll be having EMBA students attend the info session and participate in the competition. There’s a lot of interest from them in acquisitions, and it will be a fun opportunity to network all together.

text: For me, I think about 2.41 being the standard list price that can only be changed by trade. As a retailer, you can choose to adjust your target price and margin, but those targets are only achievable if the brand offers you a trade discount. So for question 3, the retailer decided that they wanted to adjust price to be a BOGO and lower their margin (so they don't screw over the brand) and the brand wants to help them make that happen so they offer trade to reduce the VC from its original $2.41. Does that help?

Every year, Baylor University hosts an *MBA Ethics Case Competition* and *the Marriott School has been invited once again to participate*. This year's competition will be held on the *Baylor campus November 9-10* (NO MBA classes Nov 8-10).

Please complete <https://byu.az1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_8c5iu4JXa5fK75A|this short survey> *by midnight tonight (10/4)* if you are interested in being considered. If you are selected, *your travel and board will be paid for* by the MBA Program.

_If you have any questions, feel free to reach out of Brad Owens, Marriott School Ethics Faculty, at <mailto:bpo@byu.edu|bpo@byu.edu>._

text:
:delta: For first-years interested in Delta Air Lines, it’s not too late to apply for the MBA Supply Chain Internship, which still has a few open slots for interviews this Friday. :delta:

Even if you don’t think of yourself as a supply chain person, there are a lot of general management skills you’ll learn in this internship. I spent my summer in meetings with operations, finance, and legal directors as I spearheaded a request-for-proposal with deicing providers for a few airports. It was a stretching experience but I learned a ton!

Applying and interviewing for the supply chain role does not preclude you from going through the process with the commercial strategy team in December/January either. Just get your face in front of the company and hopefully good things will happen!

If you are interested, *be sure to apply on Handshake before Wednesday at 10pm*: <https://app.joinhandshake.com/stu/jobs/8254627?ref=preview-header-click&search_id=fbadef29-ec1b-40d0-96c4-7fe9c5ed385c>

And also *attend the info session this Thursday at 6pm. RSVP here:* <https://app.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1379802?ref=events-search>

text:
FIRST YEARS! Reminder: Rothschild & Co investment banking info session is tomorrow. If you are interested in IB even a little, this is your chance to check it out (if you plan to apply for their internship, you should be there). Additionally, if you are interested in IB exit opportunities (i.e., PE or search fund), IB is a valuable place to start and you should go.

Time/place: Wed Oct 4 from 6:00-7:00pm in TNRB 280.

Some benefits you can expect from a role with Rothschild & Co:
• Opportunity to directly shape and determine the course of the world
• Strategic position where you will work directly with the C-suite of multiple companies
• Group of ambitious, supportive and collaborative people
• $175k base salary (pro-rated for internship) + annual bonus of up to $175k (full-time)
• $60k starting bonus + $10k moving stipend
• 5 weeks vacation + banking holidays + unlimited sick days
• Daily free dinners + ubers + other perks
If you plan to attend, register on handshake (link below).

<https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1363807?ref=events-search|https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1363807?ref=events-search>

I recommend dressing up for the event. For reference, a suit without a tie is how I'll be dressed. Join the IB Slack channel to connect/share tips with others: <#C0433QH7AA3|investment-banking>

text:
1st (and 2nd) years:

The Q&A info-session for class bidding starts @11am in W240, after which you can start to finalize your schedule for Winter 2024.  There are some good resources to help you decide what classes to take, like
• the BYU schedule builder (<https://commtech.byu.edu/auth/registrar/schedule-builder/>)
• an excel file I made that is floating around and is partially outdated (make sure to update)
• or the bidding website itself (<https://services.byu.edu/mba>).
If, during the Q&A, you languish due to want of food, please stop by *W122 @11:30am* and hear students talk about the Cougar Strategy Group LDB (CSG) for winter 2024! CSG is sponsoring Chick-fil-A (will have some veggie and GF options) if you come listen to our 20min presentation.

Reasons to attend:
• CSG has LDB options for international students that doesn't effect your visa status.
• We will share information about a new consulting class that teaches "how to consult," which is applicable to all tracks.
• Opportunity to gain actual team leadership experience while in school.
• With combination of CTS (HR) and CSG (Bus. Strat), this is one of the best LDBs to learn about and launch a career into business consulting.
See you at 11:30am in W122 tomorrow!

text:
Need help preparing for interviews? Worried about case interviews? Need to get to the next level? WE GOT YOU!

With a lot of people going into interviews I wanted to point out a great resource available to all. If you need any help with interviews, especially case interviews please use these mentors! The below is posted and pinned in the SCA chat for your convenience!

Case Mentors - they can do a 45-minute case, mini-case/strategy questions, resume review, and behavior interviews.  If you desire something other than a 45min case please let them know prior.
Please schedule time with these mentors. If the available times don't work please get in touch with the case mentor and they will try to accommodate your schedule.
List of Case Mentors, with calendars invites, and emails. (you can also slack them)
• Benjamin Williams
    ◦  <mailto:benjamincolewilliams@gmail.com|benjamincolewilliams@gmail.com>
    ◦ <https://calendly.com/benjamincolewilliams/60min>
• Jake Preslar
    ◦ <mailto:jacobpres4@gmail.com|jacobpres4@gmail.com>
    ◦ <http://calendly.com/jacobpres>
• Taylor Brooks
    ◦ <mailto:taylorleebrooks@gmail.com|taylorleebrooks@gmail.com>
    ◦ <https://calendly.com/taylorleebrooks/case-prep>
• Melissa Stone
    ◦ <mailto:melissaelaineking75@gmail.com|melissaelaineking75@gmail.com>
    ◦ <https://calendly.com/melissakingstone/60min>
• Brett Holden
    ◦ <mailto:brettsholden@gmail.com|brettsholden@gmail.com>
    ◦ <http://calendly.com/brettsholden>
• Kevin Baize
    ◦ <mailto:kevin.n.baize@gmail.com|kevin.n.baize@gmail.com>
• Tyler Hill
    ◦ <mailto:t.wakefield.hill@gmail.com|t.wakefield.hill@gmail.com>
    ◦ <https://calendly.com/t-wakefield-hill>

*<https://www.signupgenius.com/go/10C0D4DADA62BAAF49-44564636-chili#/|Chili Competition!>*
Get ready to spice things up at our MBA Chili Competition! It's time to put your culinary skills to the test and show off your family's secret chili recipe.
Bring your A-game, your appetite, and your competitive spirit. Whether you're a chili connoisseur or a first-time cook, this event is for you. Prizes, bragging rights, and, of course, the coveted title of "MBA Chili Champion" are up for grabs.
Don't miss out on this sizzling opportunity to connect, compete, and enjoy some delicious chili!
Award categories will include: Best Overall, Most like Mom's, Best Smoked Chili, and Best Sweet & Spicy Chili.

text:
We're having an info session on buying a business on October 17th, 5p -6p.
• What the economics of buying a business look like
• What the benefits to buying a business are
• How to start looking for a business to buy
• Listen to experiences from a few BYU MBA grads that have bought businesses
• Intro to the Acquisition Case Competition that will take place in November ($1000 cash prize to the winner) -- 1st/2nd years can enter
It's open to anybody 1st or 2nd years -- just give us a thumbs up or something and we'll get some pizza or food.

And for a brief overview of buying check this WSJ article out: <https://www.wsj.com/articles/m-b-a-s-latest-pitch-investors-startup-business-school-spac-11647457255>

text:
*Attention 1st Years- Cougar Capital Info Session 10/10*

Come join us on Tuesday evening to hear more about one of the MBA’s LDBs, Cougar Capital! Cougar Capital is an investment fund modeled after VC/PE firms where students get the chance to research, present, and ultimately invest in companies alongside some of the top investment firms in the state/nation. There will be multiple members of the current Cougar Capital class there to share their experiences and backgrounds. We will also go over important dates/requirements to get into Cougar Capital. See below for a little more information:

When: This Tuesday (10/10) from 5-6 PM
Where: W208

Any and everyone is welcome! Please come with questions, and we will try to answer all of them!

text:
Utah- and BYU-wide service opportunity

It's going to be an awesome event where *every university in Utah is having a service project on the same day*. BYU's service project will include a blood drive, making bed mats for refugees and homeless populations, writing cards to the elderly, and even going off-campus to build homes for those in need. It will be an amazing event and we're hoping to spread the word to as many people as possible.

text:
Last reminder to register for the BYU + Silicon Slopes: Growth Venture Connect Meet & Greet

*Registration will close at 4pm today.  If you register your resume will be sent out in the resume book to the company.  You can still come to the event if you do not register; however, your resume will not be included in the resume book.*

This event is a networking event NOT a hiring event but this is an opportunity to get your name on the radar of local growth stage companies.  We will have another event in the winter semester that will be focussed on hiring.

Attire: Business casual and please wear your MBA name tag

text:
Making another plug for this... if you came back from your internship and thought "I wish I had a more meaningful opportunity to go after" this is for you:

We're having an info session on *buying a business* on October 17th, 5p -6p, room TBD.
• What the economics of buying a business look like
• What the benefits to buying a business are
• How to start looking for a business to buy
• Listen to experiences from a few BYU MBA grads that have bought businesses
• Intro to the Acquisition Case Competition that will take place in November ($1000 cash prize to the winner) -- 1st/2nd years can enter
^^The Acquisition Case Comp will be on  :rotating_light: *Saturday, November 18th* :rotating_light: at the new Kiln in Provo. It will be an awesome chance to pitch your acquisition idea(s) to potential investors.

It's open to anybody, 1st or 2nd years -- just give us a thumbs up so we have a headcount for food.

text:
:large_blue_circle: :black_circle: :red_circle:
   :large_yellow_circle: :large_green_circle:

Who out there likes the Olympics?!  :hand: Huge Olympic news the last few days: the IOC made it official that they will award the 2030 and 2034 Winter Olympics at the same time this summer right before the Paris 2024 :fr: Olympics!  Salt Lake is currently the only city in talks with the IOC for 2034 so things are looking very promising for Salt Lake to host another Olympics :us:!!  With this news, there is a ton of buzz on social media.  My work with the Salt Lake Olympic Committee is focused on capturing that buzz and it would be a _*HUGE*_ help if you followed/liked @SLC2030 on facebook, twitter, and instagram!  Use the links below or type "SLC2030" in social media search bars.  Thanks!!

<https://twitter.com/SLC2030>
<https://www.facebook.com/SLC2030/>
<https://www.instagram.com/slc2030/>

text:
Hey everyone, I know there’s been a TON of announcements, so I wouldn’t say this unless it was important! Opening social for the Adam Smith Society TOMORROW at 5:30pm!
1. How do I RSVP? 
Go to <#C0499MYJVPZ|adam-smith-society> channel and react to this thread I shared here!
2. WHY should I RSVP?
If you, a) want to eventually listen to interesting speakers, b) network with classmates, or c) enjoy great discussion and food around free market principles!
3. WHAT is the commitment level?
ABSOLUTELY NONE! This is a no fee club, and contrary to Megan Lesa’s comments, you get WAY MORE than you paid for! Partially because we’re funded by the Manhattan Institute from the East Coast
4. BUT “I don’t want to get notifications from a channel that I may not have time to pay attention to!”
If you look at how to use slack, you’ll see that you can mute notifications from specific channels. 2nd year pro-tip for anyone who’s experiencing stimuli overload after mid terms and the first month and a half of the program have “humbled”/ abased you and your sense of competency.

text:
Hey Everyone! We have a great MBA networking event coming up! Oct 24th at 6pm in the Hinckley Building East Conference room. We are inviting all past MBA SCA Alumni and friends of the program that what to see BYU MBA's get into strategy or consulting roles!

Consulting Companies committed: *McKinsey, Bain, PwC, Slalom, Cicero, Clozd* (looking to get more to come)
Strategy Roles/Companies Committed: *Bill, Dees Limited, School Leadership Alliance, Henry Schein One, Security Metrics, BYU TV* (looking to get more to come)

If you are interested in Consulting it will be a great opportunity!

If you are interested in Strategic roles or strategy roles this will be a great opportunity!

Many of these companies are looking for interns and full-time roles or have connections to opportunities!

There will be a soda bar and Hors d'oeuvres
*NOW FREE for everyone - we have decided to drop the fee (thank you, anonymous supporter)*
Business Casual

text:
Hi everybody! If you're still looking for full-time opportunities or internships, think about going to the *SHPE* conference this year. It's a conference as big as National Black, but this year is going to be  in Salt Lake City between 1-5 Nov. The career fair will be Friday and Saturday that week. Be mindful:

• SHPE is the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers. What does it mean?
    ◦ Many of the companies are looking for engineers, but I've seen also roles related to operations, finance, and marketing. Take a look at the companies, which in my opinion I like <https://web.cvent.com/event/17a1aac6-42d1-4323-a534-1a8db35a2187/websitePage:61ab3099-32e7-4e56-96e1-27a86adeca63|better> than the ones this year at National Black.
    ◦ Do you have to be Hispanic to be part of SHPE? Absolutely not! Please come!
    ◦ It's for professionals and students (undergrads and graduate students), so MBA roles might be limited

If you want an MBA to grow or sustain your business venture, ask yourself: What are the persistent problems I’m facing in trying to start or grow my business? Which business concepts can I learn at school that may help me solve these work-related problems? How can I quickly introduce and integrate these concepts into my company? If you want an MBA to help you get a promotion, ask yourself: Which work practices, if changed, would accelerate my promotion? Which business concepts from school can I apply to change these work practices? How can I leverage the improvements I make to advocate for a promotion? If you want an MBA to help you switch industries, companies, or roles, ask yourself: What does my current career path look like? How do I want to change it? What experiments can I conduct at school (and at work) to try out this new path? How can I leverage these experiments to change careers? If you want an MBA to figure out your career goals, ask yourself these questions: What are some possible post-MBA careers that might interest me? What are my personal values, and how do these possibilities align with those values? text:
As announced by Dan at the WIM event last week, this is (to our knowledge) the first time a female faculty panel has been held for the Marriott School. #bigdeal 

This has been a dream in the making and is open to all students in the Marriott School. The MBA will also be hosting a recruiting booth at the event- please invite anyone interested in the program too! 

The five faculty on the panel are:
Dean Madrian, Dean of the Marriott School
Bonnie Anderson, Associate Dean
McKenzie Rees, Organizational Behavior/Management Professor
Bekki Brau, Global Supply Chain Professor
Hannah Judd, Accounting Professor
#powerhouses 

And yes- there will be food. :relaxed: We would love to have as many MBAs as possible! 

Register now and submit questions for the panel here: 
<https://marriott.byu.edu/event/femalepanel2023|https://marriott.byu.edu/event/femalepanel2023>

text:
Hey Everyone! There will be companies with full-time and internship opportunities at this networking event tomorrow Oct 24th at 6pm in the Hinckley Building East Conference room. We are inviting all past MBA SCA Alumni and friends of the program that what to see BYU MBA's get into strategy or consulting roles!

Consulting Companies committed: *McKinsey, Bain, PwC, Slalom, Cicero, Clozd* (looking to get more to come)
Strategy Roles/Companies Committed: *Bill, Dees Limited, School Leadership Alliance, Henry Schein One, Security Metrics, BYU TV* (looking to get more to come)

If you are interested in Consulting it will be a great opportunity!

If you are interested in Strategic roles or strategy roles this will be a great opportunity!

*Many of these companies are looking for interns and full-time roles or have connections to opportunities!*

There will be a soda bar and Hors d'oeuvres
*NOW FREE for everyone - we have decided to drop the fee (thank you, anonymous supporter)*
Business Casual

text:
Hey Everyone! It’s finally here! There will be companies with full-time and internship opportunities at this networking event today Oct 24th at 6pm in the Hinckley Building East Conference room. We are inviting all past MBA SCA Alumni and friends of the program that what to see BYU MBA's get into strategy or consulting roles!

Consulting Companies committed: *McKinsey, Bain, PwC, Slalom, Cicero, Clozd* (looking to get more to come)
Strategy Roles/Companies Committed: *Bill, Dees Limited, School Leadership Alliance, Henry Schein One, Security Metrics, BYU TV* (looking to get more to come)

If you are interested in Consulting it will be a great opportunity!

If you are interested in Strategic roles or strategy roles this will be a great opportunity!

*Many of these companies are looking for interns and full-time roles or have connections to opportunities!*

There will be a soda bar and Hors d'oeuvres
*NOW FREE for everyone - we have decided to drop the fee (thank you, anonymous supporter)*
Business Casual

text:
:large_blue_diamond: *Important* Blue Lounge Updates for <!channel> :large_blue_diamond:

1. We will be changing the door code to the MBA lounge this week on *Friday morning.* The *new door code will be 20234* (think of the school year 2023-24). We know that the mid-year change is a pain and tried to hold off on changing it, but the existing code is pretty broadly known outside the MBA and we've had multiple issues of non-MBAs spending time here late in the evening/on the weekends and want to keep things locked and safe.
2. A huge THANK YOU to <@U03PKR5GQUQ> and her helper <@U03LMGSGBQC> for decorating the lounge for us - it looks amazing!!

text:
:rotating_light: BETA COURSE TEST AUDIENCE NEEDED :rotating_light:<!channel>

Hi Friends, I have a HUGE favor to ask!

I'm currently building out a _*Intro to Total Rewards*_ course for my business and need some volunteers to serve as "beta testers". All you need to do is show up to my presentation on *Friday, November 3rd from 12:30-2:30pm,* ask any questions you may have about Total Rewards, and provide me with some feedback via a survey link I'll send out after the class.

I'm hoping to get _at least_ 20 attendees - both 1st and 2nd years - and will bribe you with treats! :slightly_smiling_face: If you have any specific questions about Total Rewards that you would like me to talk about, shoot me a DM!

I'm testing out a function on my website (please don't review the website...it's currently in a pathetic state of despair :tired_face:) and would LOVE if you would reserve a seat through this link: <https://millennialhrgal.com/ola/services/beta-course-intro-to-total-rewards-byu-mba-audience>

Thank you, thank you, thank you!!! :two_hearts:
-Ashlee

Applications for the November Talkapalooza is LIVE! Our theme next month is to celebrate *Native American Indian/Alaska Native Heritage Month and Veterans Day*. text:
DEAR <!channel>,
️
Quick reminder about tomorrow's volleyball event. Let's step out from the study sessions and dive into some fun on the court! :volleyball:

:date: *WHEN?* TOMORROW (FRIDAY), from 6pm to 8pm
 :round_pushpin: *WHERE?* SFH Building - We've got 2 courts waiting just for you!

*Here's why you should swing by:*
1. :person_doing_cartwheel: *Get Active, Stay Healthy!* A fun way to balance out the rigorous MBA grind.
2. :handshake: *Forge Lasting Friendships!* Beyond projects and exams, the bonds you make here can last a lifetime.
3. :person_in_lotus_position: *Relieve Some Stress!* What's better than serving and spiking away the day's tensions?
4. :tada: *All About Fun!* Whether you're a pro or a newbie, come join the laughter and the game.
Your MBA journey isn't just about studies; it's also about the connections you make. Tonight's the perfect chance to strengthen those ties!
See you there, and don't forget your sporty vibes! :rocket:

• Talking stocks
• Interested in joining Silver Fund
• Like challenging yourself
• Learning new things
• Or want to buy a Koenigsegg car, a Richard Mille watch, a Maltese Falcon Yacht, or a Gulfstream jet someday!

text:
A friendly reminder about the Marriott School Female Faculty Panel this Wednesday from 6-7:15pm.

This is an incredible opportunity to ask the panel ANYTHING you’ve ever wondered about working in the Marriott School, managing life/family/career balance, the journey of academia, etc.

Friends and family are invited to attend. :) The MBA is also using this as a recruiting event for prospective students if you have friends considering the program! 

The event is for EVERYONE. :heart: 

Please register today and submit your questions to help us get a final count: 

<https://marriott.byu.edu/event/femalepanel2023|https://marriott.byu.edu/event/femalepanel2023>

We can’t wait to see you there!! 

Huge thanks to the WIM presidency for making this possible: <@U03L4GUGBF1> <@U03LN7V9M0U> <@U03LG7DNSUV> <@U03LXQCM22D> <@U03LYFFN24R>

text:
I'll add on to what Chad said, you can add any class to your cart and the software will attempt to register you for those classes.

The MBA puts a general restriction on all MBA classes except those who won the bid.  MBA class restrictions will be removed next week (Thursday, I think?) so that anyone can add the class.

Greetings! Thanks for your interest in performing in the Christmas program! I'm going to give as many details as we have so far—feel free to leave the channel if these logistics won't work for you!

We will be performing at a Christmas event that the MBA program is _likely_ hosting on December 8. This date is not finalized yet so don't advertise anything until we hear more. This will _not_ be the big formal dinner thing that the MBA puts on every year (apparently often called "MBA prom"... I think Gail Miller came and spoke at it last year... _that_ event has yet to be scheduled).

<@U05AN3RPDFU> and I have just found out that we have a slot to perform 2 songs with the choir. Should be pretty easy! (Since we know everyone is busy!) Apparently we won't have time in the program for any smaller musical numbers, so for those of you who were interested in doing a number by yourself, save it for a later day I guess!

We'll be nailing down a rehearsal schedule soon, which I suspect is what most people need to know about before they commit... stay tuned and we'll let you know!

text: Also, blue forge or cougar capital?
blocks: [{'type': 'rich_text', 'block_id': 'e1ov8', 'elements': [{'type': 'rich_text_section', 'elements': [{'type': 'text', 'text': 'Also, blue forge or cougar capital?'}]}]}]

text:
Essentials (imo):
• ETA - Tom Peterson
• VC/PE - Gary Williams
• Venture Studio Practicum: Tom Peterson
New Venture Launchpad is also good (idk when it’s taught) from what I hear. 

Neither Blue Forge nor Cougar Capital are for startups. 

Blue Forge connects you to multiple entrepreneurs and gives you exposure to various projects in various disciplines. Want more finance or deal making skills? Sign up for one of the projects in BF and gain reps. You put in the effort to connect with and impress these entrepreneurs. In turn, equity opportunities and partnerships present themselves. 

Cougar Capital you’ll get some exposure to in VC/PE Class. If you want to get into VC or PE, it’s a must, imo. The network is incredible and there’s a golf event every year for alumni. People make great connections that way and Gary has done a great job to curate a great group. It’s not inaccessible to non members, you just take an extra step to connect. 

Neither Blue Forge nor Cougar Capital is the end-all-be-all option. Take what is best for you.

text:
It's the same class with no really good reason for being split into two terms. If you sign up for one you should sign up for the other one. Regarding bidding, the first one should be bidding priority since the second one builds off the first one.

Also, this is NOT simply an Excel class. There is a separate class for that. This is a financial modeling in Excel class. Lots of people dropped 2nd term last year because I don't think they understood that distinction. That being said, this was by FAR the most valuable, hands on class for finance in the entire MBA for me.

text: They are two “term” classes. So technically A goes until like late February/early March, and then B goes for the rest of the semester. But both of them combined make up the entire semester

text:
AT&T is holding an info session for their Finance Leadership Development Program Monday, October 9 at 4pm! They are recruiting for both interns and full-time.

This is a great opportunity for anyone looking to do a corporate finance rotational program at a Fortune 30 company (in Dallas, TX).

The event is technically virtual, but we are planning to meet in a TNRB classroom with some type of food (details forthcoming).

Both I and <@U03LXQH03LZ> interned there and are planning to return full-time. We will be at the event to chat with anyone interested.

Register for the event on Handshake! (especially if you want the link to join virtually)

<!channel> everyone in GFA should come be a part of this, I promise after your internships you'll be thinking "how can I get a more meaningful job" and this is it:

We're having an info session on *buying a business* on October 17th, 5p -6p, room TBD.
• What the economics of buying a business look like
• What the benefits to buying a business are
• How to start looking for a business to buy
• Listen to experiences from a few BYU MBA grads that have bought businesses
• Intro to the Acquisition Case Competition that will take place in November ($1000 cash prize to the winner) -- 1st/2nd years can enter
^^The Acquisition Case Comp will be on Saturday, November 18th at the Kiln in Provo. It will be an awesome chance to pitch your acquisition idea(s) to potential investors.

It's open to anybody 1st or 2nd years -- just give us a thumbs up so we have a headcount for food.

It's also the only time I'll use the @ channel so whoever moderates don't shoot me.

text:
*Homecoming Finance Pro-Sem: Interview Prep*

This Friday we will have an interview prep Pro-Sem. As it’s Homecoming, first years will have the great opportunity to practice with and meet second years and alumni.

Also because it’s Homecoming, it will be fun! Since it’s *from 1-2:15pm* there’s no need for breakfast, so we will have candy and door prizes instead. Come for a laid-back, sweet time with friends, networking, and interview practice. We will still be in w208 and you are welcome to come even if you didn’t register for the full homecoming event. See you Friday!

text:
*Financial Modeling Preview Pro-Sem*

We are very excited to have Professor Brandon Muirhead come for our Pro-Sem this Friday. He will introduce himself, do a couple demo modeling exercises with us, and share his wisdom. He teaches one of the most popular classes in the program. It is full for next semester with a long wait list. If you’re enrolled or are curious for next year, please come!

It’s back to normal this week, so it will be from 9:30-10:45am in room w208. A light breakfast will be provided.

text:
*Tonight*, Tim Pehrson, the CEO of Integris Health, will be hosting an Information Session for Administrative Summer 2024 internships (<https://integrisok.com/careers/career-development/administrative-fellowship/administrative-internship-program>).

The internships roles in finance, operations, strategy, and HR.

They will also be discussing part-time remote jobs (10+ hours a week; $15-$17 per hour) that begin in January.

*Date: Thursday, October 19th*
Time: 5:00 - 6:00 PM MT
Location: TNRB W-310
*Crumbl cookies will be provided

PLEASE REGISTER ON HANDSHAKE AHEAD OF TIME:

<https://byu.joinhandshake.com/events/1401428/share_preview>

text:
Hi friends! On behalf of MBAMA I wanted to say that y’all are doing an amazing job!! We know it’s crazy with midterms coming up, recruiting every second, lack of sleep, plus personal and family stuff. 

You are doing SO MUCH BETTER THAN YOU THINK YOU ARE! 
I have loved seeing you guys helping each other out! 

I have an hour or so on Friday after prosem and would love to help with interviewing, resumes, or go on a walk and chat! :) please DM me and we’ll find some time! And if you just need a friend, please reach out to any MBAMA member, we are here for you and want to help!

text:
:alert:Alumni Event:alert:

On *October 20,* the program will be running a multi-class alumni event. We want to get as many marketing students in attendance. We do have two pro sems this morning, so this is *NOT* a priority for 1st years.

Second years, I *HIGHLY* encourage you to attend. Lunch will be served. And *Dave Boyce* will be speaking to the Marketing students. He asked me how interactive it could be, I think it's gonna be a wild party.

Registration link below. Great opportunity to network with alumni (and get a free lunch)

<https://marriott.byu.edu/event/mba-reunion2023/home>

:alert:Friday's Pro Sems:alert:

We had some scheduling issues, so we'll still have our two Pro Sems in the morning. I *highly encourage* the first years to come to the pro sems in the morning (you have permission to skip the alumni event).

We'll have *Neal Armstrong* from 9:30-10:45 and *Todd Rowe* from 11-12:15 (this will be a completely different topic than his talk he'll give in Glenn's class)

<!channel> :alert::alert:FREE LUNCH THIS THURSDAY:alert::alert:
Happy Happy Tuesday! We have some incredible good news for you! The MBAMA leadership knows that midterms can be tough, and we are thinking about each of you a lot. If you need someone to talk to or need a little study break, we are here for you!!!
*For now, we want to FEED YOU!*
Come hungry this Thursday, we will have your lunch covered with some yummy subway wraps!
_**Exclusively for our valued paid MBAMA members, as our resources are limited, and we want to ensure our paying members are well-fed!*_
_**If you have any dietary restrictions, please feel free to comment or reach out to me privately - we've got your needs covered!*_

Second years, I *HIGHLY* encourage you to attend. Lunch will be served. And *Dave Boyce* will be speaking to the Marketing students. He did a test run of his presentation and it was fant-tabulous

text:
Gamestop has a January year end. This means that most of their year actually falls into the calendar year before. I.e. the 10k filed as 2021 contains data from the 12 months leading up to that. So 11 of the 12 months were actually in 2020. So the column in the income statement is labeled 2020.

But then the question in the homework asks for the year ENDED.

So basically the question is asking you for 2020 and 2019. Which means that you need to be taking the information from the 2019 and 2018 income statements

text:
I don’t think these have been shared- there are two pre-PhD classes offered in the winter if you are even considering the thought or want to know more about different types of research in management. A lot easier to figure out now if you are interested or not. :)

There is one for OB and one for strategy. They were immensely helpful for me- small groups with faculty from each of those departments coming in to speak each week. You get a lot of personal interaction and time to deep dive into all the facets of the profession. Great exposure if even considering the path. 

Both 3 credits. Message me if interested!

text: <@U05DD0R2J6R> Long story short, I would highly recommend it! It's been one of my favorite (and most valuable) courses in the MBA program. What makes it so great is the practicality of the content. We work on building a series of hard data skills in the context of real-world problems. Assignments consist of taking these problems end-to-end from raw data, analysis, and visualization, all the way to recommendations on a slide. Everything is done in the frame of how it would look in a consulting engagement and the course is taught by two full-time consultants (one from McKinsey, one from Bain). The course does assume some prior exposure to Python, R, and SQL.

text:
I would say that the only class I've taken than properly teaches consulting grade decks is MBA 593R Advanced Strategy Consulting, taught by 2 MBB consultants from Bain and McKinsey.

I took logistics last semester and I'm taking right now both Advanced Strategy and Consulting, and Advanced Strategy Analytics.

Advanced Strategy and Consulting won't teach you about decks, you will have to create them, but you will bring your knowledge + classmates about decks.

Logistics is great for presentations, the communications part and the deck. Having said that, the deck they use is not MBB consulting grade. It will help your presentation skills for sure, but the deck is not a self sustained document you give to clients.

text:
If your goal is to create consulting grade decks, I would go directly to Strategy and Analytics instead.

There're some nuances though. If I remember correctly, the consultant that teaches the section of consulting decks will not be able to be on campus next semester because of work (he will teach remotely probably). The other thing is that the class relies heavily on Python and R to do analysis and then translate that to a deck. If you don't like programming, it could make things harder.

text:
Do you want an A?
• Global Business is totally manageable if you rely on your group. Similar to marketing load, maybe lighter
• Strategy is A LOT of reading and video watching, but they are by far the most relevant case studies, and its extremely useful. Heavy workload if you want to do well. 
• Entrepreneurial Innovation: pretty minimal in terms of readings and coursework. Heavy on group work and idea generation. 
• Analytics: Talk to someone who liked the class. It wasn't much work for me.

Hello friends! Thank you so much for being willing to help on Saturday! I talked with my mom today and she was almost in tears because of your willingness to help! :pray::skin-tone-2:

This probably won’t be the most fun activity you have participated in, so keep that in mind :) west long sleeves or a flannel to prevent scratches and if you have work gloves, bring them (and extras too if you have them) 

I would love to set up a carpool, with 12 of us, are there about 2 others who would be willing to help drive? It’s about 1 hour 15 mins away from Provo. 

My mom would like to feed everyone dinner but I also know I don’t want to monopolize your precious Saturday…  :joy: so we’ll work something out, but there will be food after! 

Once again thank you! May God bless all you wonderful, kind people!! 
:heart: :heart: :heart:

text:
<!channel> Hey everyone! The house next door to us is being prepped to be a rental! Here is the info on it if there is anyone still looking for housing. Please read the whole post!

The address is 362 W 370 S American Fork UT 84003. 20-25min from school depending on traffic.

Available as early as 10/20/2023.

The home is having new carpet put in it. Move in date can also be negotiated. But the sooner the better.

The landlord would be the same as our landlord. His name is Gary Hogland and is honestly THE nicest guy. You treat his homes nice and he treats you with the same respect.
3 bed/2.5 bath with a 2 car garage. It's about 2000 sq ft. Open layout with an unfenced yard and couple garden boxes in the back. No Washer/Dryer currently, but Gary is willing to work that out if needed.

No pets.

Rent is negotiable, Gary discounts it for MBA students and he 100% prefers them. He did mention it would be less than $2,000 a month but you'll need to contact him for the final cost.

Gas+electric could be anywhere between $200-250 a month. I'm guessing this because that's what we pay next door for roughly the same size home. Gary covers water/garbage/sewer costs in the rent price. Gary is also willing to work with you if you end up taking an internship out of the state. We decided to sign until the end of the whole MBA program in our lease next door.

The neighborhood and ward is STELLAR and quiet. Seriously. Lots of kids (and I mean LOTS) but the road is quiet and the most noise we hear is when we open the windows at night and you can hear the Highway nearby. Elementary school is great! We have a 1st grader and he loves his school. There are enough kids that they actually have 2 school busses for our neighborhood.

Let us know if you any questions, or feel free to reach out to Gary. His number is <tel:801-836-4485|801-836-4485>

text:
Hi!! I’m looking for a private room for rent

 - I’d love to live with other MBA roommates, but not a deal breaker
 - I have furniture in storage and can provide my own if needed. 
 - My husband and I are doing long distance while I finish the program, and he’ll be visiting me every month
 - I would love to bring my cats with me, so a place that allows cats would be superb! But if not I’d just leave them with my husband back home.
 - Private bathroom would be nice, but also not a deal breaker
 - The closer to campus the better, but I do have a car and can be flexible

Thanks!!

text:
Below is the info for the *HR Advisory Board Conference on 11/17*! This will take the place of our HR Pro Sem that day :slightly_smiling_face:

The BYU Human Resources Advisory Board is hosting a conference to meet with you, here at BYU, *November 17, 2023*. A box lunch will be catered by Brick Oven after the opening session where you will get to meet in small groups with the Advisory Board members and ask them any questions you would like.

	During the main breakout sessions, they will speak on topics such as:
1)      Building a successful career in HR and navigating the real world
2)      How to build your brand, network, and trust as an HR professional
3)      Becoming a strategic HR partner mean by balancing strategy with operational excellence
4)      Learning the importance of Change Management, AI/Chat GPT and the impact of technology in HR
5)      The art of becoming a leader and developing leaders
6)      Hybrid work – implications on you AND implications on the employee experience

	We ask that you *<https://marriott.byu.edu/event/obhrstdntconf2023|register here> BY NOV 1ST* so we may order lunch for you. Please take a minute to <https://marriott.byu.edu/event/obhrstdntconf2023/speakers|read up on each Advisory Board Member> to see what companies they work for. It’s a great opportunity to network with them.

text:
Here's what's listed in the Syllabus:

"Project Milestone 3: Find an Organization and Identify an HR Process to Analyze

After getting to know each other and establishing the working rules of the team, you need to identify an organization that you are interested in working with, as well as an HR-related process that they would like your help analyzing. As a team, create a list of 5-6 organizations that would be intriguing to work with. Your “pitch” to each organization might go something like this:

“My name is _________ and I am an MBA student at BYU. I’m taking a Human Resource Management class and we have been asked to conduct a service consulting project to help us learn how to analyze and improve HR processes in organizations. Could we meet to discuss some of the HR processes in your organization and how we might be able to help you analyze and improve your HR processes?”

When you meet with a representative from an organization, help them understand the process and timing of the project and try to find an appropriate issue they are wrestling with, or would like to wrestle with, related to the concepts we will study in class (recruiting, reward systems/retention, training, onboarding, etc.).

Once you have identified an issue, turn it into a research question that includes “how” and “what” and could be answered through collecting data. Example questions might include:
• How effective is the organization’s current approach to recruiting and what could be done to make it better?
• How effective is the organization’s current approach to onboarding and what could be done to make it better?
You will often have to approach more than one organization, so start early trying to identify your organization. You will also have a much more enjoyable experience if you pick an organization that you are excited about rather than one that is merely convenient! When you have identified an organization and a topic, upload the name of the organization, your client contact, and the question you are planning to research on Canvas so we can make sure you are heading down the right path."

Is this helpful? Or are you looking for additional clarification?

text:
Hi peeps. I ran a prompt on GPT with the content for our HR midterm + HBS Barbara Norris case and it provided me some pretty useful questions to prepare for tomorrow. I though it would be helpful for you as well. I asked TA about it and it is not illegal on the subject perspective, so thought someone else would benefit from it.

Here are the 40 questions:

Certainly! Here are 20 MBA level test questions based on the specified HR perspectives and topics related to the "Barbara Norris: Leading Change in the General Surgery Unit" case study:
1. Evidence-Based Management:
    ◦ Explain the difference between correlation and causation. How can Barbara Norris use these concepts to analyze the factors affecting staff morale in the General Surgery Unit?
2. Evidence-Based Management:
    ◦ Apply the Good Theory concept to identify potential interventions Barbara Norris could implement to improve staff morale and reduce turnover in the General Surgery Unit.
3. Interdependence and Contingency Theory:
    ◦ Analyze the interdependence within the General Surgery Unit. Which type of interdependence (pooled, sequential, reciprocal, or intensive) is most prevalent? How does this affect the unit’s performance?
4. Meaningful Work and Job Characteristics Model:
    ◦ Evaluate the job characteristics in the General Surgery Unit using the Job Characteristics Model. How can Barbara Norris enhance meaningful work experiences for her staff?
5. Job Crafting and Calling:
    ◦ Discuss how job crafting and a sense of calling can be integrated into the work culture of the General Surgery Unit to improve employee engagement and satisfaction.
6. Universal Needs and Personality Tests:
    ◦ Compare Maslow’s Hierarchy of Needs, ERG Theory, and Two-factor Theory. Which theory do you think is most relevant to understanding the motivations of the nursing staff in the General Surgery Unit? Justify your answer.
7. Unity in Diversity and Managing Whole-Brained Teams:
    ◦ Describe how unity in diversity can be achieved in the context of the General Surgery Unit. How can Barbara Norris manage whole-brained teams effectively?
8. Recruiting and Selection:
    ◦ Design an ideal hiring process for recruiting nursing staff in the General Surgery Unit. Include the methods, assessments, and interviews you would use.
9. Recruiting and Structured Interviews:
    ◦ Explain the importance of structured interviews in the hiring process. Provide examples of competency questions that Barbara Norris can use during interviews.
10. Job Offers and Negotiation:
    ◦ Identify common issues and mistakes made during the job offer process. How can Barbara Norris avoid these issues and negotiate job offers effectively?
11. Job Offers and BATNA:
    ◦ Define BATNA (Best Alternative to a Negotiated Agreement). How can Barbara Norris determine her BATNA during the negotiation process with potential candidates?
12. Reward Systems and SMART Goals:
    ◦ Propose a reward system for the General Surgery Unit based on SMART goals. How can SMART goals be aligned with the hospital’s overall strategic objectives?
13. Compensation Problems and Motivation vs Performance:
    ◦ Analyze potential compensation problems that might arise in the General Surgery Unit. How can these problems impact employee motivation and performance?
14. Social Identity Theory and Communication:
    ◦ Apply Social Identity Theory to explain the communication challenges Barbara Norris might face while implementing changes in the General Surgery Unit. How can she overcome these challenges?
15. Evidence-Based Management and Stakeholders:
    ◦ Discuss the role of stakeholders in evidence-based management. How can Barbara Norris ensure that she considers the perspectives and needs of all stakeholders in her decision-making processes?
16. Dynamic Work Design and Contingency Theory:
    ◦ Apply the Contingency Theory of Structure to propose an organizational structure that aligns with the dynamic work design required in the General Surgery Unit.
17. Individual Differences and MBTI/Big 5:
    ◦ Compare the MBTI (Myers-Briggs Type Indicator) and Big 5 personality tests. Which one do you think is more useful for understanding the preferences and behaviors of nursing staff? Justify your answer.
18. Job Crafting and Employee Engagement:
    ◦ Explain how encouraging employees to craft their jobs can enhance employee engagement. Provide examples specific to the healthcare industry.
19. Recruiting and Unstructured Interviews:
    ◦ Discuss the disadvantages of unstructured interviews in the hiring process. How can bias be minimized during unstructured interviews in the General Surgery Unit?
20. Reward Systems and Motivating Potential Score:
    ◦ Calculate the Motivating Potential Score (MPS) for a nursing role in the General Surgery Unit. How can the reward system be designed to enhance the MPS for employees?

1. Evidence-Based Management and Organizational Learning:
    ◦ How can evidence-based management facilitate organizational learning within the General Surgery Unit? Provide specific examples from the case.
2. Congruence Model and Organizational Effectiveness:
    ◦ Apply the Congruence Model to analyze the alignment between the General Surgery Unit's strategy, tasks, formal processes, and individual skills. What recommendations would you make to improve congruence?
3. Interdependence and Team Dynamics:
    ◦ Discuss the concept of reciprocal interdependence in the context of the General Surgery Unit. How can fostering strong reciprocal interdependence enhance teamwork and collaboration among staff members?
4. Job Characteristics Model and Employee Satisfaction:
    ◦ Identify three job characteristics from the Job Characteristics Model that are lacking in the General Surgery Unit. How can enhancing these characteristics improve overall employee satisfaction and performance?
5. Job Crafting and Employee Well-being:
    ◦ Explain how job crafting can contribute to employees’ sense of well-being and work-life balance in a high-stress environment like the General Surgery Unit.
6. Universal Needs and Individual Differences:
    ◦ Compare and contrast Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs and the Big Five personality traits theory. How can understanding both theories help Barbara Norris in managing diverse personalities within her team?
7. Unity in Diversity and Cultural Intelligence:
    ◦ Discuss the concept of cultural intelligence in the context of achieving unity in diversity within the General Surgery Unit. How can cultural intelligence improve communication and collaboration among a diverse workforce?
8. Recruiting Strategies and Diversity:
    ◦ Design a recruiting strategy that promotes diversity and inclusion within the General Surgery Unit. What specific measures would you take to attract candidates from diverse backgrounds?
9. Structured Interviews and Bias Reduction:
    ◦ Explain how structured interviews can help reduce bias in the hiring process. Provide examples of structured interview questions that can effectively assess candidates’ qualifications.
10. Job Offers and Negotiation Strategies:
    ◦ Describe the importance of the Zone of Possible Agreement (ZOPA) in job offer negotiations. How can understanding ZOPA assist Barbara Norris in reaching mutually beneficial agreements with potential candidates?
11. Reward Systems and Performance Management:
    ◦ Discuss the role of rewards in performance management within the General Surgery Unit. How can a well-designed reward system align with the unit's performance goals and motivate employees?
12. Employee Engagement and Social Identity Theory:
    ◦ Apply Social Identity Theory to explain how employees' identification with their roles in the General Surgery Unit can enhance overall employee engagement. What managerial strategies can leverage social identity for positive outcomes?
13. Dynamic Work Design and Flexibility:
    ◦ How can dynamic work design principles be integrated into the General Surgery Unit to accommodate flexibility in staffing and adapt to changing patient needs? Provide specific examples.
14. Change Management and Stakeholder Analysis:
    ◦ Conduct a stakeholder analysis for the General Surgery Unit. Identify key stakeholders and their interests. How can Barbara Norris manage these stakeholders effectively during the change process?
15. Ethical Considerations in Recruiting and Selection:
    ◦ Discuss ethical considerations that Barbara Norris should be mindful of during the recruiting and selection process. How can ethical recruitment practices enhance the unit's reputation and employee morale?
16. Motivating Potential Score and Employee Performance:
    ◦ Calculate the Motivating Potential Score (MPS) for a nursing role in the General Surgery Unit. How can a high MPS lead to improved employee performance and job satisfaction?
17. Team Diversity and Decision-Making:
    ◦ Explain how diverse teams, in terms of skills, background, and experiences, can lead to more effective decision-making in the healthcare setting. Provide examples from the case study.
18. Performance Appraisals and Continuous Feedback:
    ◦ Compare traditional performance appraisals with continuous feedback systems. Which approach do you think is more suitable for the General Surgery Unit, and why?
19. Employee Recognition and Psychological Safety:
    ◦ Discuss the importance of employee recognition in creating a psychologically safe workplace environment. How can Barbara Norris implement effective recognition programs to foster psychological safety among her staff?
20. Talent Development and Succession Planning:
    ◦ Develop a talent development and succession planning strategy for the General Surgery Unit. How can identifying and nurturing talent within the unit contribute to its long-term success?

Paccar is coming to campus today. This company does sponsor for some of their roles. This is a company that design and manufacture premium trucks (which must be a plus if you're into country music), located in Bellevue (WA).

From 6 to 7pm - Tanner Building Room W240.

text: <@U05AK5HHLVB> has joined the channel

Hi all. I've been asked for this info from several of you now, so throwing it out here in the channel.

How I would approach preparing for an IB internship:
• Priority #1: Network to get interviews
• Priority #2: Study technicals (400 Q guide and the IB book, especially chapters 1-3)
• Priority #3 (after receiving internship offer): Use an online service like Training the Street or Wall Street Prep to improve modeling, accounting, PowerPoint etc. skills based on what you need so you can get a full-time return offer.
Investment banking book is here:
<https://investmentbankingbook.com/>

'}, {'type': 'text', 'text': 'I’m'}, {'type': 'text', 'text': ' looking for the 400 Q Guide and I am seeing a lot of versions. Which one would you recommend?'}]}]}]

text: Honestly, not sure. I nabbed one from the undergrads last year. Any of them should work as long as it's recent. As far as I know, the interviewers aren't likely going to ask you the exact questions off the guide, but they will ask things similar to those questions. I would recommend studying the book, then using the 400 Q guide to test your knowledge/practice interviews, if you have the time. If limited on time, focus on ch 1-3 of the book (valuation section) and the "basic" (not "advanced") technical sections of the 400 Q guide. I'll look into it a bit more next week and get back to you. Ping me if I don't by Tuesday night.

text:
<@U05A7HEBCDV>, to help answer your question more. Elon is and HAS been sued over his use of "X". At this point, it just became a money war. He knows that he can pay off anyone he wants to be able to illegally use the trademark "X".

Microsoft, in particular, has trademarked "X" since 2003 in its association with the X-Box.
Here's an <https://www.wsj.com/tech/elon-musk-twitter-x-rebrand-trademark-bird-logo-b7433fb6|article> to learn a little more about this. Start about halfway through for the trademark information.

text: Discontinuing cars is vaguely referenced in the manual, but I haven't seen any one button to press. The manual also says, "Check the B2B Only—sometimes called Remove From Market—checkbox to stop selling a vehicle to consumers. text:
7 minutes total. There are maybe 1 or 2 questions, but because everyone did the same project, Prof. Christensen doesn't usually do a ton of questions.

If you touch base on the following questions in your presentation, you can use the whole 7 min:

Questions to guide your thinking as you prepare (*these questions should NOT directly outline your presentation*):

1. What have you learned?  _This is certainly the most important question._
2. How did things go? What went well? How did you shoot yourselves in the foot?
3. What was your strategy? Did it change over the course of the periods or is it the same as when you started? If so, how and why did you change it? How effective do you feel your strategy was?
4. What would you do differently if you could do it again? Why?

text:
My daughter will be 9 in January. One of her favorite birthdays was decorating cakes ( but 12 cakes is a lot!)

We have also done painting- just bought blank canvases and supplies at a craft store. I have done it with YW and we had them take turns painting one of the other girls. That was fun.

You could also do friendship bracelet making. 

Serve some type of food where they are in charge of making in it/assembling (candy kabobs or necklaces, caramel apples, even a waffle bar or nacho bar)

text:
For those who haven't experienced the testing center before, here are some resources:
• <https://testing.byu.edu/testing-hours|Testing center hours and the forecasted number of people taking tests on each day> (Yesterday was a red day, which means that I would have needed to plan to wait in lines longer; during my undergrad, there were several times where I waited in line 1.5+ hours, here is a <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z_bfkOZRAJw|7 minute video> of a person walking from start to finish of a testing center line in 2016)
•  Camera of the testing center lines, both in the BYU app and on the <https://testing.byu.edu/|testing center homepage>
• <https://testing.byu.edu/taking-tests|FAQ> 
    ◦ Dress and Grooming Standards are enforced pretty stringently. Haha, they even have razors guys can buy if they forgot to shave and don't have a Beard Waiver. 
• Here is the page of <https://testing.byu.edu/my-exams|when late fees happen for each test>. Normally, if you take a test on one of the last days, you are given a $5 fee because the testing center wants to incentivize people to not all take the exam on the last day at the last hour. Our test is due on next Saturday, but Professor Snow told the testing center that the test closes on Tuesday, so currently, the testing center says we won't need to pay a late fee.

text:
*Case Overview Pro-Sem* 

This Friday, the finance Pro-Sem will be a “how to” lesson in casing.

Come learn from the outstanding finance professor himself, Ben Iverson, about how to handle quantitative cases and what he looks for in a case. Then, get a student perspective from VCIC competition champion Adam Navar as he talks about tips for cases and case competitions.

Once again, this will be 9:30-10:45am in w208. A light breakfast will be provided. We look forward to seeing you there!

text:
:fire::fire::fire:Entrepreneurship Pro-sem:fire::fire::fire:
Friday October 6th from 11-12:15 in W308
We'll be hearing from Chad Ingram this week. Since founding <http://Distro.io|Distro.io> two years ago, Chad has been on a rocketship. He's founded several companies since graduating from BYU in 2013, living through the ups and downs of entrepreneurship. He did have a successful exit previous to starting Distro, with his company JUMP being acquired. Check out their website to see how they're revolutionizing offshore hiring.

<!channel> IMPORTANT ANNOUNCEMENT FOR PRO SEMS NEXT WEEK :alert:

Next weekend is homecoming :byu: The MBA administration is inviting all CURRENT MBA's to participate in the annual alumni event. This is a unique and NEW opportunity. Attached is the itinerary for *NEXT FRIDAY, October 20th from 12-5 p.m.*
:eyes: _*THIS EVENT WILL TAKE THE PLACE OF PRO SEMS*_, so please REGISTER in order to attend.
During this event, there will be lunch with all alumni and current students, breakout sessions with alumni and current students from your track, and then more time for networking with all alumni and current students along with a final keynote speaker.
:link: *Please register at <https://marriott.byu.edu/event/mba-reunion2023/home|this link> ASAP* :slightly_smiling_face:

text:
*Homecoming Finance Pro-Sem: Interview Prep*

This Friday we will have an interview prep Pro-Sem. As it’s Homecoming, first years will have the great opportunity to practice with and meet second years and alumni. 

Also because it’s Homecoming, it will be fun! Since it’s *from 1-2:15pm* there’s no need for breakfast, so we will have candy and door prizes instead. Come for a laid-back, sweet time with friends, networking, and interview practice. We will still be in w208 and you are welcome to come even if you didn’t register for the full homecoming event. See you Friday!

*Financial Modeling Preview Pro-Sem*

We are very excited to have Professor Brandon Muirhead come for our Pro-Sem this Friday. He will introduce himself, do a couple demo modeling exercises with us, and share his wisdom. He teaches one of the most popular classes in the program. It is full for next semester with a long wait list. If you’re enrolled or are curious for next year, please come!

It’s back to normal this week, so it will be from 9:30-10:45am in room w208. A light breakfast will be provided.

This is reminder not to forget about the upcoming Johnson & Johnson PLDP Online Career Event. If you aspire to have a career in operations/procurement, we invite you to sign up to the live session happening on:
October 4th at 12 pm EST/ 6 pm CET / 12 am HKT (next day)

During the presentations and audio Q&As, you'll gain an in-depth look at Johnson & Johnson PLDP, as well as how to build a successful long-term career with Johnson & Johnson.

<!channel> This was posted last night in another channel, so I want to make sure people are aware:

From <@U03SZAWQBM4>:
FIRST YEARS! Reminder: Rothschild & Co investment banking info session is tomorrow. If you are interested in IB even a little, this is your chance to check it out (if you plan to apply for their internship, you should be there). Additionally, if you are interested in IB exit opportunities (i.e., PE or search fund), IB is a valuable place to start and you should go.

Time/place: Wed Oct 4 from 6:00-7:00pm in TNRB 280.

Some benefits you can expect from a role with Rothschild & Co:
• Opportunity to directly shape and determine the course of the world
• Strategic position where you will work directly with the C-suite of multiple companies
• Group of ambitious, supportive and collaborative people
• $175k base salary (pro-rated for internship) + annual bonus of up to $175k (full-time)
• $60k starting bonus + $10k moving stipend
• 5 weeks vacation + banking holidays + unlimited sick days
• Daily free dinners + ubers + other perks
If you plan to attend, register on handshake (link below).

<https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1363807?ref=events-search|https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1363807?ref=events-search>

I recommend dressing up for the event. For reference, a suit without a tie is how I'll be dressed. Join the IB Slack channel to connect/share tips with others: <#C0433QH7AA3|investment-banking>

*BYU + Silicon Slopes: Growth Venture Connect*
*Meet & Greet*

*What:* This is an MBA-only event where you can connect with local Growth companies. Not all are hiring at this moment, but the connections you make will be invaluable.

*Where:* N. Eldon Tanner Building (TNRB), Brigham Young University, Provo, Utah 84602
Room 410 (4th floor)

*When:* Wednesday, October 11th, 2023

*Time:* 6pm – 9pm *Light refreshments provided*

We hope to see you there! _*Register <https://marriott.byu.edu/event/growthventure2023/registration|here> or by using the QR code.*_

text: Hey first years!  I interned at Dell last year, but my internship did not come from on campus recruiting.  I interned with Dell Technologies Services (DTS) which doesn't recruit on campus, but does recruit MBA and graduate level interns.  I was talking with some people in DTS HR and they sent me some QR codes for internships in DTS.  There are some business, analytics, and data science MBA/graduate level internships.  Scan the QR codes and apply if you are interested!

text:
AT&T is holding an info session for their Finance Leadership Development Program Monday, October 9 at 4pm! They are recruiting for both interns and full-time.

This is a great opportunity for anyone looking to do a corporate finance rotational program at a Fortune 30 company (in Dallas, TX).

The event is technically virtual, but we are planning to meet in a TNRB classroom with some type of food (details forthcoming).

Both I and <@U03LXQH03LZ> interned there and are planning to return full-time. We will be at the event to chat with anyone interested.

Register for the event on Handshake! (especially if you want the link to join virtually)

<https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1393746?ref=events-search>


I understand AT&T has a solid marketing development program too, so if you are interested in that, you may want to come just to learn more about the company (although the focus of this meeting will be the finance development program).

text:
Last reminder to register for the BYU + Silicon Slopes: Growth Venture Connect Meet & Greet

*Registration will close at 4pm today.  If you register your resume will be sent out in the resume book to the company.  You can still come to the event if you do not register; however, your resume will not be included in the resume book.*

This event is a networking event NOT a hiring event but this is an opportunity to get your name on the radar of local growth stage companies.  We will have another event in the winter semester that will be focussed on hiring.

Attire: Business casual and please wear your MBA name tag

text:
Hey Everyone! We have a great MBA networking event coming up! Oct 24th at 6pm in the Hinckley Building East Conference room. There will be all sorts of great companies represented there! Including but not limited to McKinsey, Bain, PWC, Slalom, Cicero, Bill, and many more! We are inviting all past MBA SCA Alumni and friends of the program that what to see BYU MBA's get into strategy or consulting roles!

There will be a soda bar and Hors d'oeuvres
Free for SCA members and $3 for non-members
Business Casual

Hey Everyone! We have a great MBA networking event coming up! Oct 24th at 6pm in the Hinckley Building East Conference room. We are inviting all past MBA SCA Alumni and friends of the program that what to see BYU MBA's get into strategy or consulting roles!

Consulting Companies committed: *McKinsey, Bain, PwC, Slalom, Cicero, Clozd* (looking to get more to come)
Strategy Roles/Companies Committed: *Bill, Dees Limited, School Leadership Alliance, Henry Schein One, Security Metrics, BYU TV* (looking to get more to come)

If you are interested in Consulting it will be a great opportunity!

If you are interested in Strategic roles or strategy roles this will be a great opportunity!

Many of these companies are looking for interns and full-time roles or have connections to opportunities!

There will be a soda bar and Hors d'oeuvres
*NOW FREE for everyone - we have decided to drop the fee (thank you, anonymous supporter)*
Business Casual

text:
Hey friends! I know this is a busy week for many of us, wanted to keep a few things on your radar regarding recruiting/networking events in the near future:

*Info Sessions*
• Dell – 10/24 (:exclamation:TOMORROW:exclamation:), 5:00 PM - 6:30 PM in TNRB 130
    ◦ Focused on Marketing internships
    ◦ Register in Handshake here: <https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1317534|https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1317534>
• The Pennant Group – 10/25, 5:00 PM - 6:00 PM in TNRB 164
    ◦ Focused on Entrepreneurship Full-time roles
    ◦ Register in Handshake here: <https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1302329|https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1302329>
• Pelion VP – 11/6, 5:00PM - 6:00 PM in TNRB W210
    ◦ Pelion is a Venture Capital firm, but the info session is not track specific, focused on internships
    ◦ Register in Handshake here: <https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1333983|https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1333983>
*Office Hours*
• The Pennant Group – 10/26, 9:00 AM - 5:00 PM in TNRB W461
    ◦ Focused on Entrepreneurship Full-time roles
    ◦ Register in Handshake here: <https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1302331|https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1302331>
*Luncheon (Come & Go)*
• Dell – 11/8, 12:00 PM - 1:30 PM in TNRB W459*
    ◦ Focused on Marketing internships
    ◦ Register in Handshake here: <https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1317537|https://byu.joinhandshake.com/stu/events/1317537>
    ◦ *Keep in mind that this event may conflict with Tech Trek trips. Confirm that you'll be able to attend before registering!
Lastly, don't forget to check out these other opportunities (not in Handshake) happening soon as well:

• 10/24 (:exclamation:TOMORROW:exclamation:), 6:00 PM - 7:00 PM: <https://byumba.slack.com/archives/C0ZCSJTC5/p1698081442281729|MBA Strategy & Consulting Networking Event, Sponsored by SCA>
• 10/26, 5:00 PM - 7:00 PM: <https://byumba.slack.com/archives/C6VUTH16Y/p1698096000620959|Dell Women in Management Top Golf Networking Event>
• _*Not strictly a recruiting event but important:_ 10/26, 11:00 AM (Marketing only): <https://byumba.slack.com/archives/C05ALCU697Y/p1697777380824809|Mandatory Info Session with Brittany Bennion for anyone interested in Dell> (DM Brittany if you are interested but not able to attend)
If you know of any recruiting events missed here, please drop them in the thread below!

text:
Hey Everyone! It’s finally here! There will be companies with full-time and internship opportunities at this networking event today Oct 24th at 6pm in the Hinckley Building East Conference room. We are inviting all past MBA SCA Alumni and friends of the program that what to see BYU MBA's get into strategy or consulting roles!

Consulting Companies committed: *McKinsey, Bain, PwC, Slalom, Cicero, Clozd* (looking to get more to come)
Strategy Roles/Companies Committed: *Bill, Dees Limited, School Leadership Alliance, Henry Schein One, Security Metrics, BYU TV* (looking to get more to come)

If you are interested in Consulting it will be a great opportunity!

If you are interested in Strategic roles or strategy roles this will be a great opportunity!

*Many of these companies are looking for interns and full-time roles or have connections to opportunities!*

There will be a soda bar and Hors d'oeuvres
*NOW FREE for everyone - we have decided to drop the fee (thank you, anonymous supporter)*
Business Casual
